\
## Overview\
"Vitamin C" is a song by the krautrock band Can on their 1972 album Ege Bamyasi. Clocking in at just over 3 minutes (3:34 in the original mix), it's one of the band's more structured and accessible compositions.\
\
## Musical Structure and Instruments\
The track is a funky, minimalist groove built on Liebezeit's relentless hi-hat and snare patterns, Czukay's pulsating bass, and Karoli's angular guitar stabs. Schmidt's organ adds ethereal flourishes, creating a tense, marching rhythm that builds to Suzuki's explosive chorus.\
\
## Characteristics\
It is known for its thick bass line, bouncy percussion and catchy chorus, which has Damo Suzuki repeating the line "Hey you! You're losing your Vitamin C". "Vitamin C" is one of the band's more conventional songs considering it has verse-chorus form, but is laced with psych-pop hooks and tape-loop weirdness.\
\
## Influence and Reception\
The bouncy percussion and bass make it ideal for breaks and remixes, influencing hip-hop and electronic scenes. Pitchfork has hailed it as "the best funk ever to come out of Europe," praising its tight propulsion and danceable energy.\
