## Musical Structure and Instruments\
\
The track "Seeland" is an instrumental with a calm tone, featuring simple repeated melodic figures on synth, piano and guitar. More specifically, "Seeland" offers a return to the six strings with what would become Rother's ornate "singing" style of playing.\
\
## Unique Structural Elements\
\
The track features two simultaneous tempos (metronome and wood block) that are resolved at the end of the track with a sampled rainstorm, which has an infinite number of tempos. The song counts on a simple metronomic drum beat and guitar and keyboards to produce a beautifully moody number that gently swells and wanes, until it reaches a moment of catharsis, before fading into the sound of rain falling and thunder crackling.\
\
## Musical Characteristics\
\
The track has the distinction of being the namesake for culture-jamming group Negativland's label, and evokes an absolutely aching strain of melodic gorgeousness, with Rother's guitar eloquently wailing with a Robert Fripp-in-D\'fcsseldorf grandeur.\
\
The track appears as track 2 on side one of the album, running approximately 6:51 in length.\
