\
## Intro Structure and Elements\
\
"Hallogallo" is formed out of just a few elements: a tic-tock wah-wah, almost like a click track, so endless and persistent that it appears to vanish from perception; an adamant yet muted melodic/rhythmic guitar line.\
\
## Multiple Guitar Layers\
\
"Hallogallo" is basically a ten-minute dance tune with a repetitive beat and layers of guitars and keyboards on top. More specifically, Klaus Dinger plays the motorik beat non-stop throughout the sensational 10-minute long album opener "Hallogallo", with Michael Rother's guitar (in at least four overdubbed tracks) drifting in and out of the mix.\
\
## Wah-Wah in the Recording\
\
Regarding the wah-wah technique, Rother describes using "fuzz and wah and the feedback" to play "long syrupy notes," and mentions that Klaus played "this kind of rhythmic, very interesting, also with wah pedal. In the case of 'Hallogallo,' this guitar was very important".\
\
The song features recorded melodies forwards and then backwards, with the tape turned around so that "backwards guitars mixing with the forward melodies" created additional textures.\
