## Musical Structure\
\
"Caramel" has a sugary groove that promptly dissolves into a sea of ethereal keyboards, amorphous layers and sparse chords. The track exemplifies "electronic pop at its most protean," with giddy and infectious rhythms driven by an early analog drum machine.\
\
## Motorik Groove\
\
Zuckerzeit brings together Cluster's haunted melodic sense and motorik rhythms, and the music filters influences through Harmonia's emerging motorik rhythms\'97steady, hypnotic grooves emphasizing forward momentum over complexity.\
\
## Drum Machine\
\
Rother loaned the group equipment including an Elka Drummer One drum machine. With this drum machine, the group experimented with mixing up multiple preset rhythms at once, as well as running the drum machine through echo, vibrato, and wah pedals, and cutting parts of the rhythm entirely.\
\
## Album Context\
\
The album's key elements include repetitive drum machine patterns that underpin most tracks, melodic lines from analogue synthesizers and Farfisa organ creating a sense of propulsion, and concise song lengths averaging around three to four minutes.\
